  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Dual-occupancy is not a granny flat.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          A granny flat is a dependent second dwelling &mdash; council allows it because
          a family member lives there. A dual-occupancy is a full second dwelling on
          the same lot, with no requirement for family relationship. Most importantly,
          a properly-built dual-occupancy is <strong>subdivision-ready</strong>: down
          the track when council planning controls evolve, the block can be subdivided
          and the second dwelling sold on its own title.
        </p>
        <p>
          That &ldquo;sold on its own title&rdquo; pathway is worth $300K&ndash;$600K
          on a typical Frankston South / Mt Eliza block in 2026 prices. The extra
          $40K&ndash;$80K you spend over a basic 2-bedroom granny flat to make the
          build subdivision-ready is the cheapest capital you&rsquo;ll ever raise.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What &ldquo;subdivision-ready&rdquo; actually means.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Independent services:</strong> Separate water meter, separate sewer connection, separate electrical mains (not just sub-board), separate gas if applicable</li>
          <li><strong>Independent stormwater:</strong> Own legal point of discharge, not piggybacking the main dwelling&rsquo;s system</li>
          <li><strong>Independent access:</strong> Own driveway from the street, own front gate, own pedestrian path</li>
          <li><strong>Boundary-compliant siting:</strong> All setbacks designed assuming a future title boundary running between the two dwellings</li>
          <li><strong>Independent parking:</strong> Own dedicated bay (often 2 on a Peninsula block)</li>
          <li><strong>Fire-rated separating wall:</strong> If the two dwellings share any boundary, NCC class 1a fire-rated construction</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Block size requirements.</h3>
        <p>
          Frankston City Council requires <strong>min 600m&sup2; for dual-occupancy</strong>
          (vs 300m&sup2; for a granny flat). Mornington Peninsula Shire requires
          800&ndash;1,000m&sup2; depending on the planning overlay. The block also needs
          enough frontage for two separate driveways (typically 15m+ frontage), or
          a battle-axe layout with a 4m-wide access leg to the rear unit.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Planning permit pathway.</h3>
        <p>
          Dual-occupancy never uses VicSmart &mdash; always a full planning permit with
          full neighbour notification. Decision time 90&ndash;120 days. We engage a
          planning consultant for any dual-occ in Mornington Peninsula Shire &mdash;
          the overlays add layers of design control that a general-practice architect
          won&rsquo;t catch first time. The planning consultant cost ($4K&ndash;$8K) is
          standard practice and almost always saves more than it costs.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Typical dual-occupancy budgets.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>2-bedroom dual-occ 90m&sup2; modular, Frankston City block: $185K&ndash;$220K</li>
          <li>2-bedroom dual-occ 110m&sup2; custom, Frankston South: $220K&ndash;$260K</li>
          <li>3-bedroom dual-occ 130m&sup2; Mt Eliza bay block: $250K&ndash;$320K</li>
          <li>Battle-axe rear unit + main-house facade upgrade (combined project): $320K&ndash;$450K</li>
          <li>Add $20K&ndash;$40K for coastal AS 4312 spec on Peninsula bay-side</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
